1
00:00:01,400 --> 00:00:05,220
In order to apply
anomaly detection,

2
00:00:05,220 --> 00:00:08,535
we're going to need to use
the Gaussian distribution,

3
00:00:08,535 --> 00:00:12,120
which is also called the
normal distribution.

4
00:00:12,120 --> 00:00:14,700
When you hear me
say either Gaussian

5
00:00:14,700 --> 00:00:16,814
distribution or
normal distribution,

6
00:00:16,814 --> 00:00:19,035
they mean exactly
the same thing.

7
00:00:19,035 --> 00:00:22,365
If you've heard the
bell-shaped distribution,

8
00:00:22,365 --> 00:00:24,885
that also refers
to the same thing.

9
00:00:24,885 --> 00:00:26,010
But if you haven't heard of

10
00:00:26,010 --> 00:00:28,380
the bell-shaped distribution,
that's fine too.

11
00:00:28,380 --> 00:00:30,270
But let's take a look at what is

12
00:00:30,270 --> 00:00:33,645
the Gaussian or the
normal distribution.

13
00:00:33,645 --> 00:00:35,415
Say x is a number,

14
00:00:35,415 --> 00:00:37,980
and if x is a random number,

15
00:00:37,980 --> 00:00:40,004
sometimes called the
random variable,

16
00:00:40,004 --> 00:00:42,630
x can take on random values.

17
00:00:42,630 --> 00:00:45,605
If the probability
of x is given by

18
00:00:45,605 --> 00:00:48,620
a Gaussian or
normal distribution

19
00:00:48,620 --> 00:00:51,155
with mean parameter Mu,

20
00:00:51,155 --> 00:00:55,045
and with variance Sigma squared.

21
00:00:55,045 --> 00:00:59,120
What that means is that
the probability of

22
00:00:59,120 --> 00:01:04,040
x looks like a curve
that goes like this.

23
00:01:04,040 --> 00:01:06,230
The center or the middle of

24
00:01:06,230 --> 00:01:10,790
the curve is given
by the mean Mu,

25
00:01:10,790 --> 00:01:15,920
and the standard deviation or
the width of this curve is

26
00:01:15,920 --> 00:01:20,355
given by that variance
parameter Sigma.

27
00:01:20,355 --> 00:01:22,690
Technically, Sigma is called

28
00:01:22,690 --> 00:01:24,820
the standard deviation
and the square of

29
00:01:24,820 --> 00:01:26,710
Sigma or Sigma squared is

30
00:01:26,710 --> 00:01:29,440
called the variance
of the distribution.

31
00:01:29,440 --> 00:01:32,200
This curve here shows what

32
00:01:32,200 --> 00:01:35,290
is p of x or the
probability of x.

33
00:01:35,290 --> 00:01:37,735
If you've heard of the
bell-shaped curve,

34
00:01:37,735 --> 00:01:40,870
this is that bell-shaped
curve because a lot

35
00:01:40,870 --> 00:01:43,880
of classic bells say

36
00:01:43,880 --> 00:01:46,390
in towers were shaped like

37
00:01:46,390 --> 00:01:50,140
this with the bell clapper
hanging down here,

38
00:01:50,140 --> 00:01:52,240
and so the shape
of this curve is

39
00:01:52,240 --> 00:01:54,880
vaguely reminiscent
of the shape of

40
00:01:54,880 --> 00:01:56,695
the large bells that

41
00:01:56,695 --> 00:02:00,255
you will still find in
some old buildings today.

42
00:02:00,255 --> 00:02:03,155
Better looking than
my hand-drawn one.

43
00:02:03,155 --> 00:02:05,260
There's a picture of
the Liberty Bell.

44
00:02:05,260 --> 00:02:07,570
Indeed, the Liberty
Bell's shape on

45
00:02:07,570 --> 00:02:11,350
top is vaguely
bell-shaped curve.

46
00:02:11,350 --> 00:02:15,745
If you're wondering what
does p of x really means?

47
00:02:15,745 --> 00:02:18,420
Here's one way to interpret it.

48
00:02:18,420 --> 00:02:22,030
It means that if you
were to get, say,

49
00:02:22,030 --> 00:02:25,900
100 numbers drawn from this
probability distribution,

50
00:02:25,900 --> 00:02:27,700
and you were to plot

51
00:02:27,700 --> 00:02:31,000
a histogram of these 100 numbers

52
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:32,440
drawn from this distribution,

53
00:02:32,440 --> 00:02:34,975
you might get a histogram
that looks like this.

54
00:02:34,975 --> 00:02:37,850
It looks vaguely bell-shaped.

55
00:02:37,930 --> 00:02:42,970
What this curve on the
left indicates is not

56
00:02:42,970 --> 00:02:45,010
if you have just 100 examples

57
00:02:45,010 --> 00:02:47,475
or 1,000 or a million
or a billion.

58
00:02:47,475 --> 00:02:51,580
But if you had a practically
infinite number of examples,

59
00:02:51,580 --> 00:02:53,920
and you were to
draw a histogram of

60
00:02:53,920 --> 00:02:55,810
this practically
infinite number of

61
00:02:55,810 --> 00:02:59,505
examples with a very
fine histogram bin.

62
00:02:59,505 --> 00:03:01,480
Then you end up with

63
00:03:01,480 --> 00:03:05,545
essentially this bell-shaped
curve here on the left.

64
00:03:05,545 --> 00:03:10,595
The formula for p of x is
given by this expression;

65
00:03:10,595 --> 00:03:15,665
p of x equals 1 over
square root 2 Pi.

66
00:03:15,665 --> 00:03:20,970
Pi here is that 3.14159
or it's about 22 over 7.

67
00:03:20,970 --> 00:03:25,255
Ratio of a circle's diameter
circumference times

68
00:03:25,255 --> 00:03:31,510
Sigma times e to the
negative x minus Mu,

69
00:03:31,510 --> 00:03:36,285
the mean parameter squared
divided by 2 Sigma squared.

70
00:03:36,285 --> 00:03:40,635
For any given value
of Mu and Sigma,

71
00:03:40,635 --> 00:03:44,560
if you were to plot this
function as a function of x,

72
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:46,585
you get this type of
bell-shaped curve

73
00:03:46,585 --> 00:03:48,865
that is centered at Mu,

74
00:03:48,865 --> 00:03:51,355
and with the width of
this bell-shaped curve

75
00:03:51,355 --> 00:03:55,720
being determined by
the parameter Sigma.

76
00:03:55,720 --> 00:03:59,470
Now let's look at a few
examples of how changing Mu

77
00:03:59,470 --> 00:04:03,480
and Sigma will affect the
Gaussian distribution.

78
00:04:03,480 --> 00:04:09,070
First, let me set Mu equals
0 and Sigma equals 1.

79
00:04:09,070 --> 00:04:13,845
Here's my plot of the Gaussian
distribution with mean 0,

80
00:04:13,845 --> 00:04:15,015
Mu equals 0,

81
00:04:15,015 --> 00:04:18,405
and standard deviation
Sigma equals 1.

82
00:04:18,405 --> 00:04:22,720
You notice that this
distribution is centered at zero

83
00:04:22,720 --> 00:04:28,145
and that is the standard
deviation Sigma is equal to 1.

84
00:04:28,145 --> 00:04:34,630
Now, let's reduce the standard
deviation Sigma to 0.5.

85
00:04:34,630 --> 00:04:38,085
If you plot the
Gaussian distribution

86
00:04:38,085 --> 00:04:41,265
with Mu equals 0 and
Sigma equals 0.5,

87
00:04:41,265 --> 00:04:43,110
it now it looks like this.

88
00:04:43,110 --> 00:04:44,910
Notice that it's
still centered at

89
00:04:44,910 --> 00:04:46,945
zero because Mu is zero.

90
00:04:46,945 --> 00:04:50,130
But it's become a
much thinner curve

91
00:04:50,130 --> 00:04:54,520
because Sigma is now 1.5.

92
00:04:54,520 --> 00:04:57,105
You might recall that Sigma

93
00:04:57,105 --> 00:05:00,100
is the standard
deviation is 0.5,

94
00:05:00,100 --> 00:05:03,715
whereas Sigma squared is
also called the variance.

95
00:05:03,715 --> 00:05:08,415
That's equal to 0.5
squared or 0.25.

96
00:05:08,415 --> 00:05:10,875
You may have heard
that probabilities

97
00:05:10,875 --> 00:05:12,690
always have to sum up to one,

98
00:05:12,690 --> 00:05:14,310
so that's why the area under

99
00:05:14,310 --> 00:05:16,455
the curve is always
equal to one,

100
00:05:16,455 --> 00:05:18,450
which is why when

101
00:05:18,450 --> 00:05:21,150
the Gaussian distribution
becomes skinnier,

102
00:05:21,150 --> 00:05:23,505
it has to become taller as well.

103
00:05:23,505 --> 00:05:26,595
Let's look at another
value of Mu and Sigma.

104
00:05:26,595 --> 00:05:30,120
Now, I'm going to
increase Sigma to 2,

105
00:05:30,120 --> 00:05:34,995
so the standard deviation
is 2 and the variance is 4.

106
00:05:34,995 --> 00:05:38,610
This now creates a much
wider distribution

107
00:05:38,610 --> 00:05:43,070
because Sigma here
is now much larger,

108
00:05:43,070 --> 00:05:46,250
and because it's now a wider
distribution is become

109
00:05:46,250 --> 00:05:47,930
shorter as well because the area

110
00:05:47,930 --> 00:05:50,710
under the curve is
still equals 1.

111
00:05:50,710 --> 00:05:56,655
Finally, let's try changing
the mean parameter Mu,

112
00:05:56,655 --> 00:06:00,450
and I'll leave Sigma equals 0.5.

113
00:06:00,450 --> 00:06:03,030
In this case, the center of

114
00:06:03,030 --> 00:06:07,440
the distribution Mu moves
over here to the right.

115
00:06:07,440 --> 00:06:09,360
But the width of

116
00:06:09,360 --> 00:06:11,700
the distribution is
the same as the one on

117
00:06:11,700 --> 00:06:13,680
top because the
standard deviation is

118
00:06:13,680 --> 00:06:16,905
0.5 in both of these
cases on the right.

119
00:06:16,905 --> 00:06:20,760
This is how different
choices of Mu and

120
00:06:20,760 --> 00:06:24,205
Sigma affect the
Gaussian distribution.

121
00:06:24,205 --> 00:06:27,364
When you're applying this
to anomaly detection,

122
00:06:27,364 --> 00:06:29,075
here's what you have to do.

123
00:06:29,075 --> 00:06:32,860
You are given a
dataset of m examples,

124
00:06:32,860 --> 00:06:37,185
and here x is just a number.

125
00:06:37,185 --> 00:06:41,490
Here, are plots of the training
sets with 11 examples.

126
00:06:41,490 --> 00:06:45,120
What we have to do is
try to estimate what

127
00:06:45,120 --> 00:06:48,420
a good choice is for
the mean parameter Mu,

128
00:06:48,420 --> 00:06:53,050
as well as for the variance
parameter Sigma squared.

129
00:06:53,050 --> 00:06:55,185
Given a dataset like this,

130
00:06:55,685 --> 00:06:57,095
it would seem that

131
00:06:57,095 --> 00:07:00,695
a Gaussian distribution
maybe looking like

132
00:07:00,695 --> 00:07:02,900
that with a center

133
00:07:02,900 --> 00:07:06,440
here and a standard
deviation like that.

134
00:07:06,440 --> 00:07:09,650
This might be a pretty
good fit to the data.

135
00:07:09,650 --> 00:07:12,185
The way you would compute Mu

136
00:07:12,185 --> 00:07:14,660
and Sigma squared mathematically is

137
00:07:14,660 --> 00:07:16,040
our estimate for Mu will be

138
00:07:16,040 --> 00:07:19,460
just the average of all
the training examples.

139
00:07:19,460 --> 00:07:22,400
It's 1 over m times sum from i

140
00:07:22,400 --> 00:07:24,050
equals 1 through m of

141
00:07:24,050 --> 00:07:26,585
the values of your
training examples.

142
00:07:26,585 --> 00:07:29,590
The value we will use to
estimate Sigma squared

143
00:07:29,590 --> 00:07:31,945
will be the average of

144
00:07:31,945 --> 00:07:34,510
the squared difference
between two examples,

145
00:07:34,510 --> 00:07:39,635
and that Mu that you just
estimated here on the left.

146
00:07:39,635 --> 00:07:42,870
It turns out that if you
implement these two formulas

147
00:07:42,870 --> 00:07:44,490
encodes with this value for

148
00:07:44,490 --> 00:07:47,055
Mu and this value
for Sigma squared,

149
00:07:47,055 --> 00:07:48,300
then you pretty much get

150
00:07:48,300 --> 00:07:51,500
the Gaussian distribution
that I hand drew on top.

151
00:07:51,500 --> 00:07:54,010
This will give you
a choice of Mu and

152
00:07:54,010 --> 00:07:56,950
Sigma for a Gaussian
distribution so

153
00:07:56,950 --> 00:07:58,360
that it looks like

154
00:07:58,360 --> 00:08:00,340
the 11 training
samples might have

155
00:08:00,340 --> 00:08:03,205
been drawn from this
Gaussian distribution.

156
00:08:03,205 --> 00:08:05,955
If you've taken an
advanced statistics class,

157
00:08:05,955 --> 00:08:07,545
you may have heard that

158
00:08:07,545 --> 00:08:10,320
these formulas for Mu
and Sigma squared are

159
00:08:10,320 --> 00:08:12,420
technically called the
maximum likelihood

160
00:08:12,420 --> 00:08:15,045
estimates for Mu and Sigma.

161
00:08:15,045 --> 00:08:17,340
Some statistics
classes will tell

162
00:08:17,340 --> 00:08:19,515
you to use the formula 1

163
00:08:19,515 --> 00:08:24,570
over n minus 1 instead of
1 over m. In practice,

164
00:08:24,570 --> 00:08:26,700
using 1 over m or 1 over n

165
00:08:26,700 --> 00:08:29,175
minus 1 makes very
little difference.

166
00:08:29,175 --> 00:08:31,170
I always use 1 over m,

167
00:08:31,170 --> 00:08:34,890
but just some other
properties of dividing

168
00:08:34,890 --> 00:08:39,120
by m minus 1 that some
statisticians prefer.

169
00:08:39,120 --> 00:08:41,040
But if you don't
understand what they

170
00:08:41,040 --> 00:08:42,900
just said, don't worry about it.

171
00:08:42,900 --> 00:08:46,800
All you need to know is that
if you set Mu according to

172
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:48,900
this formula and Sigma

173
00:08:48,900 --> 00:08:51,240
squared according
to this formula,

174
00:08:51,240 --> 00:08:53,385
you'd get a pretty
good estimate of

175
00:08:53,385 --> 00:08:55,770
Mu and Sigma and in particular,

176
00:08:55,770 --> 00:08:58,320
you get a Gaussian
distribution that will be

177
00:08:58,320 --> 00:09:02,220
a possible probability
distribution in terms

178
00:09:02,220 --> 00:09:04,620
of what's the
probability distribution

179
00:09:04,620 --> 00:09:06,915
that the training
examples had come from.

180
00:09:06,915 --> 00:09:10,245
You can probably guess
what comes next.

181
00:09:10,245 --> 00:09:14,415
If you were to get an
example over here,

182
00:09:14,415 --> 00:09:18,660
then p of x is pretty high.

183
00:09:18,660 --> 00:09:21,015
Whereas if you were
to get an example,

184
00:09:21,015 --> 00:09:24,915
we are here, then p
of x is pretty low,

185
00:09:24,915 --> 00:09:27,780
which is why we would
consider this example,

186
00:09:27,780 --> 00:09:30,210
okay, not really anomalous,

187
00:09:30,210 --> 00:09:31,830
not a lot like the other ones.

188
00:09:31,830 --> 00:09:34,410
Whereas an example
we are here to be

189
00:09:34,410 --> 00:09:37,230
pretty unusual compared to
the examples we've seen,

190
00:09:37,230 --> 00:09:40,935
and therefore more
anomalous because p of x,

191
00:09:40,935 --> 00:09:42,480
which is the height
of this curve,

192
00:09:42,480 --> 00:09:45,210
is much lower over here
on the left compared

193
00:09:45,210 --> 00:09:49,185
to this point over here,
closer to the middle.

194
00:09:49,185 --> 00:09:54,150
Now, we've done this only
for when x is a number,

195
00:09:54,150 --> 00:09:56,235
as if you had only
a single feature

196
00:09:56,235 --> 00:09:58,515
for your anomaly
detection problem.

197
00:09:58,515 --> 00:10:01,890
For practical anomaly
detection applications,

198
00:10:01,890 --> 00:10:05,610
you usually have a lot
of different features.

199
00:10:05,610 --> 00:10:09,230
You've now seen how the
Gaussian distribution works.

200
00:10:09,230 --> 00:10:11,740
If x is a single number,

201
00:10:11,740 --> 00:10:13,495
this corresponds to if,

202
00:10:13,495 --> 00:10:15,610
say you had just one feature

203
00:10:15,610 --> 00:10:18,385
for your anomaly
detection problem.

204
00:10:18,385 --> 00:10:21,565
But for practical anomaly
detection applications,

205
00:10:21,565 --> 00:10:23,710
you will have many features,

206
00:10:23,710 --> 00:10:28,105
two or three or some even
larger number n of features.

207
00:10:28,105 --> 00:10:31,270
Let's take what you saw for
a single Gaussian and use

208
00:10:31,270 --> 00:10:32,440
it to build a more

209
00:10:32,440 --> 00:10:34,780
sophisticated anomaly
detection algorithm.

210
00:10:34,780 --> 00:10:37,270
They can handle
multiple features.

211
00:10:37,270 --> 00:10:40,160
Let's go do that
